<dl id="n54109k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54109k">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54109k"> 109(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ and in the night &amp; at / fading of stars <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54109k"><li>FW 5.20f </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n54109k">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n54109k">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54109k">MS BL 47476a-135</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:293 <a name="ad7" href="../../FF/fdra/ada.htm#ad7">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/ad7.htm#n54109k">Draft: I.1&sect;1.7</a>/2.7</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Mohammed enjoined his followers to pray five times a day. 1. Before sunrise. 2. When the sun has begun to decline. 3. In the afternoon. 4. A little after sunset. 5. At night fall. These are the regular hours of prayer to be observed by all good Moslems, but many follow the example of their Prophet, and pray at other times as well. For it is written, &ldquo;Celebrate the praises of thy Lord what time thou risest <mark>and in the night and at the fading of the stars</mark>.&rdquo; <small> Edith Holland, <a name="EHSM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EHSM"><cite title="source">The Story of Mohammed</cite></a> (1914) 93</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
